 what I suspect will the clear favoring of Adobe=E2=80=99s tools.

What is interesting to consider is what happens if this deal is not allowed=
. Figma, as you would expect from the party with the negotiating advantage,=
 comes out pretty well: the company gets a $1 billion breakup fee at an imp=
lied $20 billion valuation without having to actually raise money in a diff=
icult fundraising environment. Still, it=E2=80=99s not all upside: it is hu=
man nature for Figma employees to already be buying their future yachts and=
 biasing their product decisions to an Adobe future; if the deal doesn=E2=
=80=99t go through there could be both culture and product harm (particular=
ly since I fully expect Adobe to fight this in court if necessary; that=E2=
=80=99s how strategically important Figma is to them). That, perhaps, means=
 there is some upside for Adobe as well: $1 billion to sidetrack its would-=
be master is perhaps a better option than just being commoditized by a disr=
uptor without a fight.

As I detail in that Update, Figma is, from a value chain perspective, best =
understood as an operating system for design (I analogized it to Teams=E2=
=80=99 place in the value chain as far as productivity applications go; the=
 most important difference is that Figma is a much better product to use). =
Adobe does not really have anything that is competitive: yes, XD exists ( i=
n maintenance mode ( https://helpx.adobe.com/support/xd.html ) ), but XD is=
 better understood as a Sketch competitor, that is a single-user focused in=
teraction design application. What makes Figma unique is the fact it is web=
-first and thus inherently collaborative. Photoshop and Illustrator and all=
 of the rest of the Adobe applications are still necessary in a Figma-based=
 design shop, but they are planets orbiting Figma=E2=80=99s sun.

That is, in a narrow sense, an argument for why Adobe should be allowed to =
buy Figma. It doesn=E2=80=99t compete with anything Adobe sells. It is also=
, in a broader sense, why Adobe of all companies should not be allowed to b=
uy Figma: Figma fundamentally changes the design value chain in a way that =
creates the conditions for new competitive threats to Adobe=E2=80=99s appli=
cations =E2=80=94 and now they have an additional $1 billion (and, to be fa=
ir, a good number of disappointed employees) to do just that.

The Neo-Brandeis Movement=E2=80=99s Missed Opportunity
----------------------------------------------

Notice that I said that I think this was the right =E2=80=9Coutcome=E2=80=
=9D; I couldn=E2=80=99t say =E2=80=9Cdecision=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cjudgment=
=E2=80=9D because this case never made it to any sort of adjudication. To r=
eview the status of the relevant regulators:

* The DOJ leaked that it would file a lawsuit in February, 2023 ( https://w=
ww.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-02-23/doj-preparing-suit-to-block-adobe=
-s-20-billion-deal-for-figma ) ; it never filed anything, nor did the FTC.
* The European Commission issued a statement of objections ( https://www.bl=
oomberg.com/news/articles/2023-11-17/adobe-s-20-billion-figma-deal-at-risk-=
of-eu-block ) arguing that the deal harmed competition in the market for pr=
oduct design tools.
* The U.K=E2=80=99s Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) released a prel=
iminary opinion ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-11-28/adobe-=
s-20-billion-figma-uk-deal-could-harm-uk-competition ) that the deal =E2=80=
=9Ccould eliminate competition in product design software, reduce developme=
nt of new products, and remove Figma as a competitor=E2=80=9D.

I think the CMA is the closest to getting this right. The European Commissi=
on=E2=80=99s objection isn=E2=80=99t wrong, per se, but it=E2=80=99s not re=
ally what actually matters in terms of this acquisition: XD is already dead=
, and stopping the acquisition isn=E2=80=99t going to bring it back. The re=
al potential issue is in fact =E2=80=9Creduce[d] development of new product=
s=E2=80=9D, and not necessarily from Figma, but rather from the competitive=
 marketplace that Figma is positioned to foster. To put it another way, Fig=
ma isn=E2=80=99t so much a competitor to XD or Photoshop or Illustrator as =
they are a competitor to Adobe=E2=80=99s hold on the design market.

