M6Ew9ZWRw-j9g5fP1iCqKQ ) , and it=E2=80=99s another for the CMA to prove th=
at an approach rooted in reality is both possible and infinitely more effec=
tive.

The neo-Brandeis movement ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Brandeis_move=
ment ) in the U.S., meanwhile, at least as represented in the choices made =
by the FTC and DOJ, seems to be much more motivated by pure ideology and co=
rrespondingly lower degree of care in actually understanding the markets it=
 seeeks to regulate. Pursuing an easily dismissed theory of harm in the Mic=
rosoft-Activision case was one example; another is not pursuing any sort of=
 action in this case.

If, in fact, the goal is to have not just more stringent merger guidelines =
( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-12-18/us-antitrust-agencies-=
cement-merger-crackdown-with-new-deal-rules ) but also more stringent prece=
dents , then Adobe-Figma offered the opportunity to put on trial a somewhat=
 novel theory of harm: acquiring Figma would, as I noted, change the struct=
ure of the market and thus reduce long-run competition, in addition to the =
near-term competitive loss of XD. That is in-line with what the neo-Brandei=
sians say they want: mergers and acquisitions should be evaluated not just =
in terms of short-term competition and consumer welfare but also the long r=
un. And yet the FTC and DOJ never bothered to try to block this merger, rel=
ying on the U.K. to do their dirty work.

Again, I=E2=80=99m not too broken up about this specific case: I think this=
 was the right outcome. And, perhaps, the DOJ and FTC didn=E2=80=99t feel t=
hey would win with the theory of harm that I (and the CMA) articulated. Tha=
t they wouldn=E2=80=99t win was, though, clearly the case in terms of Micro=
soft-Activision, particularly after discovery yielded documents that contra=
dicted their case, and it=E2=80=99s not like that stopped the FTC; it=E2=80=
=99s getting increasingly difficult to ascribe the decision-making here to =
anything other than ideological blindness to be generous (big tech bad, and=
 the bigger the badder), and incompetence to be mean.

First, Do No Harm
-----------------

From Om Malik ( https://om.co/2023/12/18/implications-of-the-adobe-figma-de=
al-failure/ ) :

The implications of the failure of the Adobe-Figma deal are pretty clear fo=
r the startup ecosystem. If =E2=80=9Cbig tech=E2=80=9D and the next layer o=
f technology companies (such as Adobe) can=E2=80=99t buy =E2=80=9Cstartups,=
=E2=80=9D the liquidity environment is going to change for the startup foun=
ders, and of course, the venture investors. Deals, especially mid-sized dea=
ls, are part of the equation. The innovation ecosystem depends on sustained=
 outcomes =E2=80=94 a positive outcome of even one in a hundred startups ke=
eps the innovation engine chugging along.

I wrote about my worries about exactly this in 2020=E2=80=99s First, Do No =
Harm ( https://stratechery.com/2020/first-do-no-harm/?access_token=3DeyJhbG=
ciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXV=
